@node "Status window" "Amitel_English.guide/Status window"
	The status window can be found in the higher part of the emulation
window and contains the following informations :

+------------------------------------------------------------------+
|  1200 7E1n 03-Aug-93 19:27:03  00:00:00   0,00 F.  Connected     |
+--+----++++-----+-------+-------+----------+--------+-------------+
   |    ||||     |       |       |          |        |
   |    ||||     Date    Time    Duration   Cost     Status
   |    |||Handshake
   |    ||Stop
   |    |Parity
   |    Bits
   Speed

        o Speed     : 1200 to 115200 Bps.
        o Bits      : 7 or 8 bits.
        o Parity    : E (Even), O (Odd) or N (None).
        o Stop      : 1 or 2 stop bit.
        o Handshake : r (RTS/CTS), x (XON/XOFF) or n (None).
        o Date      : System date.
        o Time      : System time.
        o Duration  : Length of the current connection.
        o Cost      : Cost of the current connection (without 0,12 Fr
                      taxe connection of Télétel server).
        o State     : Connected, Unconnected, Display, Capture,
                      Printing, Configuration, Dialing, Script,
                      Downloading, Help, Modem or Minitel xxx, Page x,
                      Receiving BBT or Sending BBT, Receiving XPR,
                      Sending XPR, Macros, x = xx, y = yy, Protocol XPR
                      or Options XPR depending of action is made.
@endnode

@node "Functions keys" "Amitel_English.guide/Functions keys"
        o 10 gadgets correspond to the function keys of Minitel.

          These keys can also be accessed using the function keys of
          the Amiga (as in AMIGATEL), but also with the Menu 'Keys' :

          @{b}F1@{ub}  : Connection/End  (^SI)
          @{b}F2@{ub}  : Return          (^M)  (also with ENTER key)
          @{b}F3@{ub}  : Repeat          (^SC)
          @{b}F4@{ub}  : Guide           (^SD) (also with HELP key)
          @{b}F5@{ub}  : Index           (^SF)
          @{b}F6@{ub}  : Correction      (^SG) (also with BACKSPACE key)
          @{b}F7@{ub}  : Cancel          (^SE) (also with DEL key)
          @{b}F8@{ub}  : Previous        (^SB) (also with the upper arrow)
          @{b}F9@{ub}  : Next            (^SH) (also with the lower arrow)
          @{b}F10@{ub} : Send            (^SA) (also with RETURN key)

          @{b}Break@{ub}      : Hangup the modem
                       (send escape and disconnect sequences).
          @{b}Left arrow@{ub} : Move to previous buffer page
                       (also with the « gadget)
          @{b}Right arrow@{ub}: Move to next buffer page
                       (also with » gadget)

          In 80 column mode, RETURN and BACKSPACE keys have their
          standard action.

        * It's now possible to reconfigure the functions keys
          described below with the option Macros in the
          configuration requester.

          With the cycling gadget, it is even possible to set a string
          of 50 letters to all combinations of keys Shift, Control,
          Alt, or Amiga and a function key.

          Nevertheless, the keys F1, Shift UP and DOWN could not be
          changed.

          You can found in 'AmiTEL_Prestel.macros' file the redefined
          functions keys for Prestel Emulation.

        * The gadgets :

          @{b}OK@{ub}     : Sets the different changes.
          @{b}Load@{ub}   : Loads the macros configuration file.
          @{b}Save@{ub}   : Saves the macros configuration file.
          @{b}Cancel@{ub} : Cancels changes.

          The configuration is saved in a file called '*.macros' in
          AmiTEL's drawer. The filename 'AmiTEL.macros' is loaded
          automatically during AmiTEL's launch.
@endnode

@node "Load a file" "Amitel_English.guide/Load a file"
        o The function Display Videotex file :

          @{b}Amiga@{ub}   : Displays a file on the window of the emulator.

          @{b}Minitel@{ub} : Sends the file to the Minitel.

          @{b}Server@{ub}  : Sends the file to a graphic Videotex server
                    with #$* chars filtered.

          The display pauses after each page. Anyway, you can pause or stop
          the display at any time, using the 'Pause' and 'Stop' gadgets.
          You can also come back to previous page with the 'Return' gadget.
          If you want to send a file to a server, you must @{" return " link "Videotex Editor" 0} the
          modem of the Minitel before and after sending the file.
@endnode

@node "Screens Catch" "Amitel_English.guide/Screens Catch"
        o The function Screen Capture :

          @{b}Amiga@{ub}    : Static/Dynamic capture using Amiga format.

          @{b}Ascii@{ub}    : Static/Dynamic capture using Ascii format.

          @{b}Videotex@{ub} : Static/Dynamic capture using Vidéotex format.

          The first action on the gadget starts the saving, and the
          second one stops it. While saving Ascii and Videotext file,
          a double click on the gadget allows to save only the current
          page (static capture). While in 80 columns mode, the capture
          is only dynamic and does not take care of the current page.
@endnode

@node "Screen printing" "Amitel_English.guide/Screen printing"
        o The function Print Screen :

          @{b}Ascii@{ub}    : print the screen using Ascii format.

          @{b}Videotex@{ub} : print the Minitel screen using Videotex graphic
                     format.

          The printing is done in static mode, which means that only the
          current page is printed. An error test is done to determine
          if the printer is 'not powered' or 'out of line'. A second
          action on the gadget will stop the current printing.
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Amitel_English.guide/Configuration"
@toc "functions"
           o Color configuration :

          @{b}Monochrome@{ub} : switch the screen to monochrome colors.
          @{b}Color@{ub}      : uses Minitel colors.
          @{b}Workbench@{ub}  : uses Workbench color (default option).
          @{b}Palette@{ub}    : displays palette to define colors.

          All the colors modification are saved in the configuration
          file (AmiTEL.prefs).
          Since version 1.0, the 4 first Workbench colors are kept, and you
          can modify them to get, for example, Magic Workbench colors.
          Since version 2.1, it is possible to use AmiTEL on a 16 colors
          screen. In this case, only the 8 colors after the 8th color are
          modified and saved in the configuration file.
          Since version 3.0, in the case of using window emulation under
          Workbench screen, colors are not modified (also with MWB).
          Since version 3.1, in the case of using window emulation under
          Workbench screen, the choice of best colors are doing with
          ObtainBestPen() function. Perfect result must be done with a 32
          colors screen.

        o Screen and font configuration :

          @{b}Screen@{ub} : Display screen requester.
          @{b}Font@{ub}   : Display font requester.

          These 2 options are only available in public screen mode.

        o Serial interface configuration :

          @{b}Speed@{ub}     : Transmisson speed (1200 at 115200 bps).
          @{b}Parity@{ub}    : Parity (even, odd or none).
          @{b}Bits@{ub}      : Number of bits (7 or 8).
          @{b}Handshake@{ub} : Error handshake (none, RTS/CTS or XON/XOFF).

          @{b}Device@{ub}    : Name of serial interface.
          @{b}Unit@{ub}      : Unit number of the serial interface.

          The default values in order to use the Videotex norm are :
          1200 bauds, even parity, seven data bits and no handshake.
          The name and unit number of the device allows to use AmiTEL with
          a multi-serial card for example.

        o Modem configuration :

          @{b}Initialization@{ub} : Changes the modem initialization sequence.
          @{b}Escape@{ub}         : Changes the modem escape sequence.
          @{b}Unconnecting@{ub}   : Changes the modem disconnect sequence.
          @{b}Dialing@{ub}        : Changes the modem dialing sequence.

          The standards Hayes sequences are 'ATZ^m' for initialisation,
          '~+++~~~' for escape, 'ATH^m' disconnecting and 'ATDT' or 'ATDP'
          for dialing. You can now add control char (^a to ^_) and a 1
          second delay (~) in configuration sequences.
          Refer to your modem documentation for more information.

          Some initialisation sequences for V23 mode:

          o Hayes compatibles     : ATB2^M
          o USRobotic 28800/33600 : ATS34=8S27=16S9=100^M
          o Supra Fax 28800/33600 : AT+MS=V23C,0,1200,33600^M

        o Transfer configuration :

          @{b}Transfer@{ub} : Transfer protocol (XPR or extern).
          @{b}Protocol@{ub} : Transfer protocol name.

        o Miscellaneous configuration :

          @{b}Modem@{ub}         : Force modem use.
          @{b}OwnDevUnit@{ub}    : Use OwnDevUnit device.
          @{b}Emulation@{ub}     : Use Minitel, VT100 or Prestel emulator.
          @{b}Screen@{ub}        : Use Workbench or Public screen.

          @{b}Enter key@{ub}     : Use 'Enter' key as 'ENVOI' Minitel key.
          @{b}Buffer@{ub}        : Define buffer size of received pages.
          @{b}Statut window@{ub} : Display status information in a window.
          @{b}LogFile@{ub}       : Save connections journal in 'AmiTEL.log' file.

        o The gadgets :

          @{b}OK@{ub}      : Validate the different configuration modifications.
          @{b}Load@{ub}    : Load a configuration file.
          @{b}Save@{ub}    : Save configuration in a file.
          @{b}Macros@{ub}  : Configuration of the @{" Functions keys " link "Functions keys" 0}
          @{b}Cancel@{ub}  : Cancel the different configuration modifications
                    (except the color).

          The configuration is saved in a file '*.prefs' which is
          in the drawers ENV: and ENVARC:. The file 'AmiTEL.prefs is
          automatically loaded during AmiTEL execution.
@endnode

@node "Phonebook" "Amitel_English.guide/Phonebook"
        o Name list :

          the phonebook can contain up to 20 names of Videotex servers.

          The list allows you to select a name so as to edit its
          characteristics or call it with the 'Dial' gadget.

        o The caracteristics :

          @{b}Server name@{ub}    : Contains the name of the Videotex
                           server/service.
          @{b}Number@{ub}         : Contains the phone number of the server.
          @{b}Cost@{ub}           : Contains the communication cost.
                           (in cents/minute).
          @{b}Reduction@{ub}      : Selected when the number supports phone
                           reduced prices.
          @{b}ARexx script@{ub}   : Contains the name of the ARexx script for
                           automatic connection.
          @{b}Speed@{ub}          : Changes transmission speed.
          @{b}Parity@{ub}         : Changes the parity.
          @{b}Bits@{ub}           : Changes the number of bits.
          @{b}Handshake@{ub}      : Changes the handshake of serial interface.

          So you can have a different configuration for each name in
          the list.

          French reductions cost used :

                  6h00  8h00 12h30 13h30 18h00 21h30 22h30  6h00
        monday     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |
        to         | 50% | Full| 30% | Full| 30% | 50% | 65% |
        friday     |     |     |     |     |     |     |     |
        saturday   | 50% | Full| 30% |       50%       | 65% |
        sunday     |                50%                | 65% |

        o The gadgets :

          @{b}Up@{ub}       : Move up current field.
          @{b}Add@{ub}      : Add field to first free entry of the phonebook.
          @{b}Delete@{ub}   : Delete current field of the phonebook.
          @{b}Down@{ub}     : Move down current field.
          @{b}OK@{ub}       : Validate the changes.
          @{b}Dial@{ub}     : Automatic dialing with a modem or a Minitel 2/10,
                     and executon of the Procedure file (if it exists).
          @{b}Load@{ub}     : Loads the phonebook file.
          @{b}Save@{ub}     : Saves the phonebook file.
          @{b}Password@{ub} : Define a password to get phonebook.
          @{b}Cancel@{ub}   : Cancel the changes.

          The phonebook is saved in a file '*.phone' which stands in the
          AmiTEL drawer. The file 'AmiTEL.phone' is automatically loaded
          during AmiTEL execution.

        REMARK : Use the 'Update' command to update your old phonebook
                 (version < 2.0).
@endnode

@node "Videotex" "Amitel_English.guide/Videotex"
        o The Videotext :

          @{b}Turning@{ub}      : Send the return sequence to the Minitel modem.

          @{b}Roll@{ub}         : Send the roll sequence to the Minitel.

          @{b}Term@{ub}         : Send the 40/80 columns sequence to the Minitel.

          @{b}Minus@{ub}        : send the upper/lowercase sequence to the
                         minitel.

          @{b}Attributes@{ub}   : Change the Minitel writing attributes
                         (Reverse, Underline, Blink, Graphic, Masked,
                         Double width, double heigth, or Double size,
                         none by default)

          @{b}Letters@{ub}      : Change the letters color of the Minitel
                         (Black, Blue, Red, Magenta, Green, Cyan,
                         Yellow or White by default).

          @{b}Background@{ub}   : Change the color background of the Minitel
                         (Black by default, Blue, Red, Magenta, Green,
                         Cyan, Yellow or White).

          @{b}Reset@{ub}        : Reset all attributs, fonts and colors.

          It is not really a real Videotext editor, but only the way
          to change the attributes of the Minitel to improve the
          message writing on a server for example.
@endnode

@node "Cutpaste" "Cut/Paste"
        It's possible to cut/paste the word under mouse pointer by
        clicking on left button. It's also possible to cut/paste all the
        row by pressing SHIFT key.

        Also, the coordinates X and Y of the mouse will be displayed in
        the status window.

        If the word is a keyword (SEND, NEXT, PREVIOUS, CANCEL,
        CORRECTION, INDEX or GUIDE), the corresponding code will be
        sent.
@endnode

@node "Download" "Amitel_English.guide/Download"
        o The Transfer function :

          @{" XPR Protocol " link "xpr" 0}    : Transfer protocol libraries that you choose
                              (Moondial, BBTPro, ZModem, ...).

          External Protocol : Execute the external transfer protocol

        With XPRBBTPro, XPRMoondial and XPRZModem, the receiving and the
        sending were triggered automatically.
@endnode

@node "xpr" "XPR Protocol"
        The principal of XPR library allows all terminal emulation
        software (like AmiTEL) to be able to use a lot of external
        transfer protocols supporting XPR specifications.

        o Choose a protocol :

          By default, AmiTEL uses the Moondial protocol with the file
          XPRMoondial.library whish must be in the LIBS: drawer.
          However, it's possible to choose another protocol XPR with
          the 'Choose' option in 'Protcol XPR' menu or with
          tooltype/parameter XPR .

          During configuration saving, the name of library is saved in
          the configuration file of AmiTEL.

        o Configure  :

          This function allows to reconfigure the chosen protocol
          options XPR and to save it in files env:XPRxxxxxx and
          ENVARC:XPRxxxxx.

          For more information on protocol options, please refer to
          their own documentation.

        o Send a/many file(s) :

          This function allows to send one or many files by the
          chosen XPR protocol. The names of files must be given.

        o Receive one/many file(s) :

          This function allows to receive one or many file(s) by the
          chosen XPR protocol. The receiving drawer is required.

        It's possible to stop a transfer in progress with the gadget
        'Stop' in the status protocol window.
@endnode

@node "ARexx commands" "Amitel_English.guide/ARexx commands"
        An ARexx Port is integrated to AmiTEL and is called 'AMITEL_REXX'.
        It adds ARexx commands to existing others to control AmiTEL, for
        automatic connection to a BBS for example.

                @{" BAUD      " link "arexx_baud" 0}        @{" BEEP      " link "arexx_beep" 0}        @{" BITS      " link "arexx_bits" 0}
                @{" CAPTURE   " link "arexx_capture" 0}        @{" CLOSE     " link "arexx_close" 0}        @{" DELAY     " link "arexx_delay" 0}
                @{" DEVICE    " link "arexx_device" 0}        @{" DIAL      " link "arexx_dial" 0}        @{" DOWNLOAD  " link "arexx_download" 0}
                @{" ESC       " link "arexx_esc" 0}        @{" GET       " link "arexx_get" 0}        @{" HANG      " link "arexx_hang" 0}
                @{" HANDSHAKE " link "arexx_handshake" 0}        @{" HANGUP    " link "arexx_hangup" 0}        @{" INIT      " link "arexx_init" 0}
                @{" NUM       " link "arexx_num" 0}        @{" PARITY    " link "arexx_parity" 0}        @{" PRINT     " link "arexx_print" 0}
                @{" QUIT      " link "arexx_quit" 0}        @{" READ      " link "arexx_read" 0}        @{" REQFILE   " link "arexx_reqfile" 0}
                @{" REQINFO   " link "arexx_reqinfo" 0}        @{" REQSTRING " link "arexx_reqstring" 0}        @{" SEND      " link "arexx_send" 0}
                @{" SENDFILE  " link "arexx_sendfile" 0}        @{" TIMEOUT   " link "arexx_timeout" 0}        @{" UNIT      " link "arexx_unit" 0}
                @{" UPLOAD    " link "arexx_upload" 0}        @{" WAIT      " link "arexx_wait" 0}        @{" XPR       " link "arexx_xpr" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_baud" "BAUD command"

        o The BAUD command :

          Usage : BAUD x

          Set the speed to x bauds (1200 bauds by default)

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" BITS " link "arexx_bits" 0} @{" PARITY " link "arexx_parity" 0} @{" HANDSHAKE " link "arexx_handshake" 0} @{" DEVICE " link "arexx_device" 0} @{" UNIT " link "arexx_unit" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_beep" "BEEP command"

        o The BEEP command :

          Usage : BEEP

          Play a Beep sound and display a screen flash.

          Result : none.
@endnode

@node "arexx_bits" "BITS command"

        o The BITS command :

          Usage : BITS x

          Set the number of bits to x (1 bit by default)

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" BAUD " link "arexx_baud" 0} @{" PARITY " link "arexx_parity" 0} @{" HANDSHAKE " link "arexx_handshake" 0} @{" DEVICE " link "arexx_device" 0} @{" UNIT " link "arexx_unit" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_capture" "CAPTURE command"

        o The CAPTURE command :

          Usage : CAPTURE AMIGA | ASCII | VIDEOTEX "Filename"

          Begins the capture in the file "Filename" with the format
          AMIGA, ASCII or VIDEOTEX.

          Result : none.

          Remark : If the file exist, it will be append.

          See also : @{" CLOSE " link "arexx_close" 0} @{" PRINT " link "arexx_print" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_close" "CLOSE command"

        o The CLOSE command :

          Usage : CLOSE

          Ends the current capture.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" CAPTURE " link "arexx_capture" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_delay" "DELAY command"

        o The DELAY command :

          Usage : DELAY n

          Wait n seconds before executing the next command.
          (n = 0 to 65535).

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" TIMEOUT " link "arexx_timeout" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_device" "DEVICE command"

        o The DEVICE command :

          Usage : DEVICE "serial-name"

          Set the device to "serial-name" (serial.device by default)

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" BAUD " link "arexx_baud" 0} @{" BITS " link "arexx_bits" 0} @{" PARITY " link "arexx_parity" 0} @{" HANDSHAKE " link "arexx_handshake" 0} @{" UNIT " link "arexx_unit" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_dial" "DIAL command"

        o The DIAL command :

          Usage : DIAL PHONEBOOK x | Phone_number

          Dial the phone number #x in the phonebook or the specified
          phone_number.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" HANGUP " link "arexx_hangup" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_download" "DOWNLOAD command"

        o The DOWNLOAD command :

          Usage : DOWNLOAD "Drawer"

          Set the drawer for receiving file(s) with XPR protocol by
          default.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" UPLOAD " link "arexx_upload" 0} @{" XPR " link "arexx_xpr" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_esc" "ESC command"

        o The ESC command :

          Usage : ESC="Sequence"

          Set the escape sequence of the modem.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" INIT " link "arexx_init" 0} @{" HANG " link "arexx_hang" 0} @{" NUM " link "arexx_num" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_get" "GET command"

        o The GET command :

          Usage : GET xx yy Len

          Get the string who is at 'xx' (00 at 39), 'yy' (00 at 24)
          coordinates and with len 'Len' (0 at 255).

          Result : String can be found in RESULT var :

                   - If RESULT = "RESULT", no string present.
                   - Otherwise RESULT hold get string.

          Remark : Use 'OPTIONS results' command at the beginning of the
                   script.

          See also : @{" READ " link "arexx_read" 0} @{" WAIT " link "arexx_wait" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_hang" "HANG command"

        o The HANGUP command :

          Usage : HANGUP

          Disconnect the Modem/Minitel.

          Result : none.

          See also :  DIAL 
@endnode

@node "arexx_handshake" "HANDSHAKE command"

        o The HANGUP command :

          Usage : HANGUP

          Disconnect the Modem/Minitel.

          Result : none.

          See also :  DIAL 
@endnode

@node "arexx_hangup" "HANGUP command"

        o The HANGUP command :

          Usage : HANGUP

          Disconnect the Modem/Minitel.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" DIAL " link "arexx_dial" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_init" "INIT command"

        o The INIT command :

          Usage : INIT="Sequence"

          Set the initialisation sequence of the modem.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" HANG " link "arexx_hang" 0} @{" ESC " link "arexx_esc" 0} @{" NUM " link "arexx_num" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_num" "NUM command"

        o The NUM command :

          Usage : NUM="Sequence"

          Set the numeral sequence of the modem.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" INIT " link "arexx_init" 0} @{" ESC " link "arexx_esc" 0} @{" HANG " link "arexx_hang" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_parity" "PARITY command"

        o The PARITY command :

          Usage : PARITY EVEN | ODD | NONE

          Set the parity.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" BAUD " link "arexx_baud" 0} @{" BITS " link "arexx_bits" 0} @{" HANDSHAKE " link "arexx_handshake" 0} @{" DEVICE " link "arexx_device" 0} @{" UNIT " link "arexx_unit" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_print" "PRINT command"

        o The PRINT command :

          Usage : PRINT ASCII | VIDEOTEX

          Prints the current screen in ASCII or VIDEOTEX format.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" CAPTURE " link "arexx_capture" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_quit" "QUIT command"

        o The QUIT command :

          Usage : QUIT

          Break and unload AmiTEL.

          Result : none.

          Remark : You must use it when you run AmiTEL by an Arexx script
                   (see Amigatel_w3 for example).
@endnode

@node "arexx_read" "READ command"

        o The READ command :

          Usage : READ Len

          Get the string with len 'Len' (0 at 255).

          Result : String can be found in RESULT var :

                   - If RESULT = "RESULT", no get string or timeout.
                   - Otherwise RESULT hold get string.

          Remark : Use 'OPTIONS results' and 'TIMEOUT' commands at the
                   beginning of the script.

          See also : @{" GET " link "arexx_get" 0} @{" WAIT " link "arexx_wait" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_reqfile" "REQFILE command"

        o The REQSTRING command :

          Usage : REQSTRING "Text"

          Display a StringRequester with "Text" text and 'OK' and 'Cancel'
          gadgets.

          Result : The entered string can be found in RESULT var :

                   - If RESULT = "RESULT", 'Cancel' gadget was selected.
                   - Otherwise RESULT hold string entered.

          Remark : Use 'OPTIONS results' command at the beginning of the
                   script.

          See also :  REQFILE   REQINFO 
@endnode

@node "arexx_reqinfo" "REQINFO command"

        o The REQSTRING command :

          Usage : REQSTRING "Text"

          Display a StringRequester with "Text" text and 'OK' and 'Cancel'
          gadgets.

          Result : The entered string can be found in RESULT var :

                   - If RESULT = "RESULT", 'Cancel' gadget was selected.
                   - Otherwise RESULT hold string entered.

          Remark : Use 'OPTIONS results' command at the beginning of the
             @{"      scr" link "arexx_reqfile" 0}i@{"pt." link "arexx_reqstring" 0}

@{"      " link "arexx_reqstring" 0}    See also :  REQFILE   REQINFO 
@endnode

@node "arexx_reqstring" "REQSTRING command"

        o The REQSTRING command :

          Usage : REQSTRING "Text"

          Display a StringRequester with "Text" text and 'OK' and 'Cancel'
          gadgets.

          Result : The entered string can be found in RESULT var :

                   - If RESULT = "RESULT", 'Cancel' gadget was selected.
                   - Otherwise RESULT hold string entered.

          Remark : Use 'OPTIONS results' command at the beginning of the
                   script.

          See also : @{" REQFILE " link "arexx_reqfile" 0} @{" REQINFO " link "arexx_reqinfo" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_send" "SEND command"

        o The SENDFILE command :

          Usage : SENDFILE AMIGA | MINITEL "Filename"

          Send the file "Filename" on the Modem/Minitel or on the emulator
          screen.

@{"          " link "arexx_sendfile" 0}Result : none.

          See also :  SEND 
@endnode

@node "arexx_sendfile" "SENDFILE command"

        o The SENDFILE command :

          Usage : SENDFILE AMIGA | MINITEL "Filename"

          Send the file "Filename" on the Modem/Minitel or on the emulator
          screen.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" SEND " link "arexx_send" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_timeout" "TIMEOUT command"

        o The TIMEOUT command :

          Usage : TIMEOUT n

          Set the maximum waiting delay in seconds for executing
          AmiTEL ARexx commands (n = 0 up to 65535).

          Result : none.

          Remark : This command must be place at the beginning of the script.

          See also : @{" DELAY " link "arexx_delay" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_unit" "UNIT command"

        o The UNIT command :

          Usage : UNIT x

          Set the number of the unit to x (0 by default)

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" BAUD " link "arexx_baud" 0} @{" BITS " link "arexx_bits" 0} @{" PARITY " link "arexx_parity" 0} @{" HANDSHAKE " link "arexx_handshake" 0} @{" DEVICE " link "arexx_device" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_upload" "UPLOAD command"

        o The UPLOAD command :

          Usage : UPLOAD "filename"

          Sends the file "filename" with the XPR protocol by default.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" DOWNLOAD " link "arexx_download" 0} @{" XPR " link "arexx_xpr" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_wait" "WAIT command"

        o The WAIT command :

          Usage : WAIT "String_Of_Letters"

          Wait the receiving of "String_Of_Letters" or the defined
          delay by the TIMEOUT command to execute the next command.

          Result : If RC = 0, "String_Of_Letters" has been received.
                   If RC <> 0, waiting delay has been reached.

          Remark : It is necessary to initialize the wait delay with TIMEOUT
                   command before using this on pain of waiting a long time.

          See also : @{" GET " link "arexx_get" 0} @{" READ " link "arexx_read" 0}
@endnode

@node "arexx_xpr" "XPR command"

        o The XPR command :

          Usage : XPR "protocol_name"

          Set the "protocol_name" as the default XPR protocol.

          Result : none.

          See also : @{" DOWNLOAD " link "arexx_download" 0} @{" UPLOAD " link "arexx_upload" 0}
@endnode

@node "Help" "Amitel_English.guide/Help"

        o The gadget Help executes AmigaGuide® or MultiView, depending
          your workbench version, and loads the file AmiTEL.guide from
          the AmiTEL drawer.

        In a next release, this option should be replaced by a real
        online help using AmigaGuide.library.
@endnode

@node "Quit" "Amitel_English.guide/Quit"

        o The Quit gadget (as it is called) stops the program.

        It is not possible to quit the program during screen capture.
        If you are again connected, you must confirm your choice.
@endnode

